{{BLP sources|date=April 2014}}
'''Josef Imbach''' (born 3 December 1945 in [[Zofingen]], [[Aargau]]) is a controversial [[Switzerland|Swiss]] Catholic theologian and [[Franciscan]] [[friar]].

He studied theology and philosophy at the Pontifical Theological Faculty of St. Bonaventure in Rome 1967-1973 and from 1975 to 2002 was a professor of [[fundamental theology]] there.

In 2002, he was suspended for a year by the Franciscan authorities for (according to him) denying the possibility of miracles. He denied holding this view <ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1141/is_17_38/ai_84092217/ findarticles.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923162305/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1141/is_17_38/ai_84092217/ |date=2009-09-23 }}</ref>  and publicly protested against the "non-transparent practices" and "unqualified opinion".

Imbach was later banned from teaching in all Catholic theological faculties worldwide by the [[Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith]]. He has been living near [[Basel]] since 2005 where he teaches Catholic theology at the Evangelical Theological Faculty.

